0","1337–Male":"1337–Overleden","1339–Female":"1339–Overleden","1287–1385":"1287–1385","1291–Female":"1291–Overleden","Abt 1337":"circa 1337","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","Abt 1339":"circa 1339","1291":"1291","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1311":"1311","1287":"1287","about 1313":"circa 1313","about 1335":"circa 1335","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Of, Felixhall, Essex, England":"Felix Hall, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kildenhall Manor, Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mildenhall Manor, Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1313–":"about 1313–Deceased","1311–Male":"1311–Deceased","1313–Female":"1313–Deceased","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1339–Female":"1339–Deceased","1287–1385":"1287–1385","1291–Female":"1291–Deceased","Abt 1337":"about 1337","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","Abt 1339":"about 1339","1291":"1291","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","1400":"1400","1311":"1311","1287":"1287","about 1313":"about 1313","about 1335":"about 1335","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Of, Felixhall, Essex, England":"Felix Hall, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Kildenhall Manor, Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall Manor, Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Filiol","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Denys, Gaetan, Germain, Gilles, Herve, Jacques, Jean-Louis, Joffre, Laurette, Laurier.","French: variant of   Fillion   ‘little boy’.","History: Antoine Filion from Paris, France, married Anne (d’)Anneville in Paris <i>c.</i> 1656, died in Quebec City, QC, <i>c.</i> 1669."],"variants":[{"name":"Fillion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Gaston, Emile, Lucien, Marcel, Aime, Cecile, Donat, Fernand, Gisele, Jean Luc.","French: from Old French <i>fillon</i> ‘little boy’, a diminutive of <i>fils</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used to denote the youngest son of a family. In North America, this surname is also an altered form of the variant   Filion  , which is rare in France."]},{"name":"Filiault","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Armand, Donat, Normand, Origene.","French: variant of <b>Filiau</b> (and, in North America, an altered form of this), itself probably a variant of   Filion   ‘little boy’. The surnames <i>Filiault</i> and <i>Filiau</i> are no longer found in France. Compare   Filyaw  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":2,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":15,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":69,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan